Locality: stakeout Allen's Hummingbird, Murry Rd, Cincinnati (2021)
Observation Details: This bird was assumed to be a Rufous Hummingbird. Ric Payne got several doc shots of this hummingbird in November, including a spread tail photo. After researching, studying diagrams and consulting experts, the consensus was that R5 and R4 looked appropriately thin enough for Allen’s; however, photos can be deceiving and more were needed. We went hoping to get diagnostic photos but failed with good spread tail shots. At this point we knew it could never be called unless the bird was in hand, measured and banded. On 12/5 Allen Chartier was able to capture and band the bird and confirmed it as an Allen’s Hummingbird. This is only the second Ohio record. A big thank you to both homeowners who graciously let us view their feeders and especially to Molly who worked with Allen Chartier to have the bird banded.
Observed female lay an egg! Fledglings continue to remain in vicinity of nest and beg.

Locality: Golden Gate Park--Arboretum (San Francisco Botanical Garden)

Media notes: Perched field photo post banding.
Observation Details: I had received poor quality cell photos of a Selasphorus hummingbird coming to a feeder 35 minutes from my home. Homeowner Pam Lehnherr reports the bird was at least present the day before Thanksgiving. She confirmed she had photos on phone dating back to Dec 6. Reports she had limited storage and had deleted the earlier photos. I expected to find a Rufous which is the most common late season hummingbird in Wisconsin. Fairly quickly I ascertained when seeing the bird upon arrival that this was a HY male Rufous/Allen's. We caught the bird for banding within 5 minutes of Peter Bridge setting up the trap. Once in hand I was immediately struck by the narrow appearance of the outer two rectrices. Secondly I did not observe a notch on the outer vane of R2 which I expected should be more salient if this was a HY male Rufous. Note the appearance of R2 can be quite variable. R2 did not appear exceptionally narrow. But both Kelly Bryan and Sheri Williamson concur that the shape of R2 is within the variation for Allen's. Third, I was struck by the short tail measurement. Measurements are as follows: Wing 40.89 mm, Tail 23.6 mm, Culmen 17.06 mm, weight 3.93 g. R5 which is a difficult measurement to obtain without removal of the feather from the bird was measured by two methods. Measurement by laying the feather on the ruler came in just under 2mm, estimated at 1.9 mm. Measurement of r5 with the calipers which is more difficult to do with the feather on the bird was 2.12mm. I consider this second R5 width measurement to be over-generous to the true width of that feather. Regardless both measurements are in range and point to Allen's Hummingbird (1.6-2.5 mm Pyle, Stiles) versus RUHU (2.7-3.7 mm Pyle, 2.7-3.6 Stiles). Size index (SI), a combination of wing+tail+culmen, developed by Kelly B. Bryan from his West Texas Data set to improve separation of of similar species with statistical significance also points to this bird being comfortably in range for HY male Allen's at an SI of 81.55. SI mean for Allen's is 80,45, range 75.11-83.49; SI mean for HY male Rufous is 85.25, range 80.69-90.28. Fat on this bird was scored as 1. No pin feathers or sheathing were noted on its wing, tail or body feathers. The inner primaries 1-5 were fresh and recently grown in as were some of the wing coverts. The tail had moderate wear on the tips. The bird was released in good health. He continued to feed and remained in the banding area while we watched him and packed the banding gear.
Also an occupied nest. Melanie reports the fledgling is about 2 weeks old.
Chicks are exercising their wings and the nest can barely contain them now. Seems likely they could fledge today?

Fairly quickly I ascertained when seeing the bird upon arrival that this was a HY male Rufous/Allen's. We caught the bird for banding within 5 minutes of Peter Bridge setting up the trap. Once in hand I was immediately struck by the narrow appearance of the outer two rectrices. Secondly I did not observe a notch on the outer vane of R2 which I expected should be more salient if this was a HY male Rufous. Note the appearance of R2 can be quite variable. R2 did not appear exceptionally narrow. But both Kelly Bryan and Sheri Williamson concur that the shape of R2 is within the variation for Allen's. Third, I was struck by the short tail measurement. Measurements are as follows: Wing 40.89 mm, Tail 23.6 mm, Culmen 17.06 mm, weight 3.93 g. R5 which is a difficult measurement to obtain without removal of the feather from the bird was measured by two methods. Measurement by laying the feather on the ruler came in just under 2mm, estimated at 1.9 mm. Measurement of r5 with the calipers which is more difficult to do with the feather on the bird was 2.12mm. I consider this second R5 width measurement to be over-generous to the true width of that feather. Regardless both measurements are in range and point to Allen's Hummingbird (1.6-2.5 mm Pyle, Stiles) versus RUHU (2.7-3.7 mm Pyle, 2.7-3.6 Stiles). Size index (SI), a combination of wing+tail+culmen, developed by Kelly B. Bryan from his West Texas Data set to improve separation of of similar species with statistical significance also points to this bird being comfortably in range for HY male Allen's at an SI of 81.55. SI mean for Allen's is 80,45, range 75.11-83.49; SI mean for HY male Rufous is 85.25, range 80.69-90.28. Fat on this bird was scored as 1. No pin feathers or sheathing were noted on its wing, tail or body feathers. The inner primaries 1-5 were fresh and recently grown in as were some of the wing coverts. The tail had moderate wear on the tips. The bird was released in good health. He continued to feed and remained in the banding area while we watched him and packed the banding gear.

*Very rare; ~4th for Cape May County. Rufous-type hummer, first discovered by Evelyn Lovitz in her garden earlier this morning. Worn imm male; age/sex determined by female-type plumage aspect with extensive rufous rump and base of tail (bases to r1), directly abutting black tail tip. Also, heavily stippled throat all the way to chin made up of neatly arranged spots with even pale fringing, all indicate imm male. Several features indicate Allen's, most importantly, very narrow rectrices (whole folded tail looks narrow) with lanceolate r2 showing no notch, and very slim r5. Also, this bird is quite worn, more so than a Rufous would normally be at this date, but appropriate for the earlier breeding phenology of Allen's. There are a good number of fresh feathers coming in around the head and body, including rufous feathers on the cheeks and flanks, and green feathers on the back and nape (appropriate for adult male Allen's). A particularly large splotch of reflective orange gorget feathers may also include some new feathers. No evidence of primary molt. Defending garden from nearby Ruby-throats; "zeee-chupity-chup" chase call sounds very much like Rufous.

Observation Details: **Rare. Captured and banded by Dwayne Martin at 07:37. I obtained a variety of diagnostic in-hand photos as well as several of it feeding at the feeder and perched in a briar patch. Size smaller than RUHU, small wing and tail measurements, bird too small to reach feeding ports from feeder perch (had to perch on the side of the feeder itself, just above the perches). Extensive green back, forming an ovate shape in general as a result of rufous rump that extended onto lower back. Greenish gorget (in most lighting situations). R2 and R5 shape/size also diagnostic (refer Pyle), along with curved culmen and shape of the tips of the outer primaries (arched/hooked slightly at tips). Bird did not vocalize all day that we heard.

Media notes: Tail spread R4-R1
Observation Details: I had received poor quality cell photos of a Selasphorus hummingbird coming to a feeder 35 minutes from my home. Homeowner Pam Lehnherr reports the bird was at least present the day before Thanksgiving. She confirmed she had photos on phone dating back to Dec 6. Reports she had limited storage and had deleted the earlier photos. I expected to find a Rufous which is the most common late season hummingbird in Wisconsin. Fairly quickly I ascertained when seeing the bird upon arrival that this was a HY male Rufous/Allen's. We caught the bird for banding within 5 minutes of Peter Bridge setting up the trap. Once in hand I was immediately struck by the narrow appearance of the outer two rectrices. Secondly I did not observe a notch on the outer vane of R2 which I expected should be more salient if this was a HY male Rufous. Note the appearance of R2 can be quite variable. R2 did not appear exceptionally narrow. But both Kelly Bryan and Sheri Williamson concur that the shape of R2 is within the variation for Allen's. Third, I was struck by the short tail measurement. Measurements are as follows: Wing 40.89 mm, Tail 23.6 mm, Culmen 17.06 mm, weight 3.93 g. R5 which is a difficult measurement to obtain without removal of the feather from the bird was measured by two methods. Measurement by laying the feather on the ruler came in just under 2mm, estimated at 1.9 mm. Measurement of r5 with the calipers which is more difficult to do with the feather on the bird was 2.12mm. I consider this second R5 width measurement to be over-generous to the true width of that feather. Regardless both measurements are in range and point to Allen's Hummingbird (1.6-2.5 mm Pyle, Stiles) versus RUHU (2.7-3.7 mm Pyle, 2.7-3.6 Stiles). Size index (SI), a combination of wing+tail+culmen, developed by Kelly B. Bryan from his West Texas Data set to improve separation of of similar species with statistical significance also points to this bird being comfortably in range for HY male Allen's at an SI of 81.55. SI mean for Allen's is 80,45, range 75.11-83.49; SI mean for HY male Rufous is 85.25, range 80.69-90.28. Fat on this bird was scored as 1. No pin feathers or sheathing were noted on its wing, tail or body feathers. The inner primaries 1-5 were fresh and recently grown in as were some of the wing coverts. The tail had moderate wear on the tips. The bird was released in good health. He continued to feed and remained in the banding area while we watched him and packed the banding gear.

Locality: stakeout Allen's Hummingbird, Murry Rd, Cincinnati (2021)
Observation Details: This bird was assumed to be a Rufous Hummingbird. Ric Payne got several doc shots of this hummingbird in November, including a spread tail photo. After researching, studying diagrams and consulting experts, the consensus was that R5 and R4 looked appropriately thin enough for Allen’s; however, photos can be deceiving and more were needed. We went hoping to get diagnostic photos but failed with good spread tail shots. At this point we knew it could never be called unless the bird was in hand, measured and banded. On 12/5 Allen Chartier was able to capture and band the bird and confirmed it as an Allen’s Hummingbird. This is only the second Ohio record. A big thank you to both homeowners who graciously let us view their feeders and especially to Molly who worked with Allen Chartier to have the bird banded.

Once in hand I was immediately struck by the narrow appearance of the outer two rectrices. Secondly I did not observe a notch on the outer vane of R2 which I expected should be more salient if this was a HY male Rufous. Note the appearance of R2 can be quite variable. R2 did not appear exceptionally narrow. But both Kelly Bryan and Sheri Williamson concur that the shape of R2 is within the variation for Allen's. Third, I was struck by the short tail measurement. Measurements are as follows: Wing 40.89 mm, Tail 23.6 mm, Culmen 17.06 mm, weight 3.93 g. R5 which is a difficult measurement to obtain without removal of the feather from the bird was measured by two methods. Measurement by laying the feather on the ruler came in just under 2mm, estimated at 1.9 mm. Measurement of r5 with the calipers which is more difficult to do with the feather on the bird was 2.12mm. I consider this second R5 width measurement to be over-generous to the true width of that feather. Regardless both measurements are in range and point to Allen's Hummingbird (1.6-2.5 mm Pyle, Stiles) versus RUHU (2.7-3.7 mm Pyle, 2.7-3.6 Stiles). Size index (SI), a combination of wing+tail+culmen, developed by Kelly B. Bryan from his West Texas Data set to improve separation of of similar species with statistical significance also points to this bird being comfortably in range for HY male Allen's at an SI of 81.55. SI mean for Allen's is 80,45, range 75.11-83.49; SI mean for HY male Rufous is 85.25, range 80.69-90.28. Fat on this bird was scored as 1. No pin feathers or sheathing were noted on its wing, tail or body feathers. The inner primaries 1-5 were fresh and recently grown in as were some of the wing coverts. The tail had moderate wear on the tips. The bird was released in good health. He continued to feed and remained in the banding area while we watched him and packed the banding gear.

Media notes: Adult male Allen's Hummingbird photographed by Curtis A. Marantz on 13 October 2017 along lower Arroyo Grande Creek, Oceano, San Luis Obispo County, California.
Observation Details: We saw in association with the stand of red-flowering plants on the north side of the creek one adult male Allen’s Hummingbird and a second female or immature male Selasphorus.  Given that the male was in the same place and behaving in the same manner as a bird that I saw here in mid-September I assume it is likely to winter here.  After getting the call that the catbird had been refound we curt short our observations of these hummingbirds. The male was seen relatively well and heard giving both calls and wing-trills, but the second bird, which was also calling, was seen insufficiently to distinguish between a young male and a female.  Both birds were relatively small hummingbirds with plump-bodies, a hunch-backed posture and long, tubular bills.  On the male I noted and my photos show that the gorget was complete and iridescent red in color, that the crown and upper back were a deep, iridescent green, and that the rump, flanks, sides of the face were rufous.  I was less sure if the scapulars were rufous or green and I never saw the tail clearly.  The breast was white and I think this same color extended down the center of the belly. The second bird had a mostly white throat, but also some iridescent red in the center, lower part.  This bird was more extensively white below, but also with rufous flanks.  As I recall the face had some rufous but the back was green and I never clearly saw the rump or upperside of the tail.
Two males were doing the looping dance and making loud noise
The most impressive male we've ever had stake claim to our feeders!

Continuing stakeout found by Tom Uslan, been frequenting his feeders between ~4 pm and dusk. Adult male with many spread tail shots taken. Fully green back, head, and rump. Unnotched R2 and pin like R4 and R5. Aggressively defending feeders from Anna’s and offering great looks. Unfortunately, the bird never displayed but the date and location suggests this bird could be breeding locally. A female selasphorus was also spotted which could potentially be his mate. What an amazing find by Tom and a fantastic job documenting the spread tail. Not an easy thing to do. Many thanks for his hospitality. For those interested, you can contact Tom via his email that is on his ebird profile.

Observation Details: Continuing. First state record of Allen's Hummingbird. See attached photos. Brainard Palmer-Ball and Mark Monroe banded this bird yesterday, Oct. 7, 2023. Here are their notes... "Captured for ID and banding; released after measurements taken and banding; returned to feeder within an hour or so. HY male with circa 10 reflective gorget feathers including a few large ones along the margin of the throat/gorget, green back, rufous rump, strong rufous wash on flanks, and rects largely rufous in color. Little emargination on tip of r2, very narrow r5 (1.98 mm), first generation r1 on left side already replaced. Wing: 39.38 mm; exposed culmen: 17.83 mm; tail 24 mm; striations present in the form of one long groove over one-half length of bill. Photos and measurements shared with several other hummingbird banders with much more experience with Rufous/Allen's. All agreed with ID of Allen's."

The male did some dives but often hovered over her; she would then leave her perch and they would chase. VISITOR RULES: Park on street (not in driveway). Walk up driveway. At grassline, look into backyard at red nectar feeder. Please do not enter backyard. Masks must be worn, and social distancing practiced. Park responsibly, not blocking driveways or fire hydrant.  *RARE* Adult female Allen's, banded and confirmed by Sandy Lockerman, 12/11/20. Patchy rufous rump, lower back and flanks. Some buff on breast. Faint markings on throat, well spaced. Wing tips fall short of end of tail. Bill appears long and slightly curved. Upon careful study, notice dark cheek patch outlined with white post-ocular mark. On this day, first showed at 8:33am. Came in every 10-20 minutes all day until 4:20 pm. Sixth record for PA.

Observation Details: Continuing rarity.

*Very rare; ~4th for Cape May County. Rufous-type hummer, first discovered by Evelyn Lovitz in her garden earlier this morning. Worn imm male; age/sex determined by female-type plumage aspect with extensive rufous rump and base of tail (bases to r1), directly abutting black tail tip. Also, heavily stippled throat all the way to chin made up of neatly arranged spots with even pale fringing, all indicate imm male. Several features indicate Allen's, most importantly, very narrow rectrices (whole folded tail looks narrow) with lanceolate r2 showing no notch, and very slim r5. Also, this bird is quite worn, more so than a Rufous would normally be at this date, but appropriate for the earlier breeding phenology of Allen's. There are a good number of fresh feathers coming in around the head and body, including rufous feathers on the cheeks and flanks, and green feathers on the back and nape (appropriate for adult male Allen's). A particularly large splotch of reflective orange gorget feathers may also include some new feathers. No evidence of primary molt. Defending garden from nearby Ruby-throats; "zeee-chupity-chup" chase call sounds very much like Rufous.

Subadult male adult Allen's pending expert review.  Green back on a male selasphorus is often the hallmark of Allen's.  This bird is green-backed, but subadult male Rufous can also have green back in the fall, with more rufous on the top of the head, neck and edges of the back than an Allen's. The crown on this bird is dark grayish, arguing for Allen's.  Looking at the tail feathers in my photo 573A5366-3 below, there may be extremely slight notching but this extremely slight notching is still in line with Allen's reference photos on Sheri Williamson's  flickr site, reference noted below.  Tena Gardiner's better tail photo taken simultaneously next to us seems to nail it as an Allen's, as compared with the references on Sheri Williamson's flickr Allen's gallery, which is the strongest evidence.  The outer tail feather in my profile flight photo below also seems pinnate, arguing for Allen's.  We are told that the timing of the gorget moult is also consistent with Allen's.     Reference Footnote:  See Sheri-Williamson's Flickr Allen's Gallery and note the Huntington Beach California Allen's photo by Eric Lu (x73-3584-1 unambiguous Allen's)..R2 has a slight indentation and all the tail feathers seem identical in shape to everyone's photos of this Houston bird.

My usual duo of Allen's today. Need I say these have both been confirmed?   We expected a hard freeze last night so I took in the feeders to keep them liquid. Just before 7:00 this morning I took them back out. It was 33d so not as cold as expected. Still, as I was hanging one of them I heard Mr A impatiently waiting in the magnolia above me. By the time I got back inside the house I noted (and identified) the bird at the feeder.  Bird A has iridescent gorget feathers on the sides of its throat and a small number of darker feathers on the central throat. Note also that Mr A has a wash of light feathers on either side of his lower back. Lancelate tail feathers, narrow R5 and green back, see diagnostic photo 20 Dec, S99191485. Mr A visit: 8:26, 8:39, 8:47, 9:12, 9:29, 9:53, 10:12, 10:30, 10:47, 10:52, 11:01, 11:25. 12 visits over 179 minutes for an average of 16 minutes between visits.  Bird B is my original Allen's. It has no iridescent side feathers and a fairly large patch on its central throat. Lancelate tail feathers, narrow R5 and green back, see diagnostic photo 15 Dec, S98935894. Mr B visit: 9:07, 9:42, 10:17, 10:48 4 visits over 101 minutes for an average of 34 minutes between visits, I musta missed a few..

Observation Details: Actively defending on of my feeders.  This is first day sighted.  I want to give credit to Kelly Bryan on this ID.  Kelly Bryan  To:Kay Zagst Cc:Johana Huff Thu, Sep 10 at 4:47 PM Johana and Kay,  Well, first of all it is not a juvenile bird.  Second, it is a female.  So, you ask me why?  This bird is not in fresh juvenile plumage.  It is in old faded, worn plumage.  Note that the tips of several tail feathers are worn and that the flight feathers are faded brown, evidence that they are almost a year old now.  The 50% green central tail feathers make it a female, an older one due to the amount of rufous at the base.  A juvenile female Rufous/Allen's would have a 100% green central tail feathers.  So, it comes down to the shape of the tail feathers, especially R2s and R5s to determine Rufous/Allen's.  If I had this bird in my hand to band and the tail length measurement was less that 26mm and the R5s were less than 2.8mm, it would be an Allen's.  The shape of the R2s and R5s look good to me based on the excellent tail spread photo.  R5s appear narrow and the R2s are not overly wide and without an indentation (notch) in the outer web near the tip of the feather.  So, that is my evaluation, not 100% sure but dang close!  KBB

Continuing rarity on private property. First seen, photographed, and identified by owner as a Rufous Hummingbird on February 11, present until February 28. Today was the last day this bird was observed at this location. Actively defending the two feeders on the back porch, its usual location. The male Costa's, though, was able to win a couple of battles. Looking like a Rufous Hummingbird except for its green back and narrower R4 and R5. Could not obtain diagnostic tail photos of notched R2 today. I have seen this bird on February 16, 20, and 28, 2018.

First documented record for Inyo County  Extract from NAB report:  BIRD DOCUMENTATION BY CHRIS and ROSIE HOWARD  Photos from 16 Feb https://photos.app.goo.gl/eMxwh0VTlc4Vte1g1  DATES: Chris and Rosie: 16 Feb 2018 11:45am – 1:00 pm; Rosie and others: 20 Feb 2018 and 28 Feb 2018  Conclusions: After consulting many references, particularly Sheri Williamson’s A Field Guide to Hummingbirds of North America, 2001, and studying the photos and videos we obtained, we are convinced this is an adult male Allen’s Hummingbird •	Back color – certainly not enough to claim an Allen’s since 10% of Rufous Hummingbird males have green backs. Nonetheless, this bird did have an entirely green upper back, extending down through the center back, only changing to rufous in the lower back where it transitions to the rump and upper tail coverts. •	There are two clincher marks to separate adult male Rufous from Allen’s: 1.	Narrow outer tail feathers – we feel this bird had very narrow R3, R4, and R5. The photo below shows the two widest central R1 feathers, with R2 on either side, then R3 appears, R4, and R5 are nearly all stacked on top of each other, though the shafts are visible at their bases. 2.	Allen’s lacks the notched R2 shown on the inner web of R2 on Rufous. The photographs of this bird show tapered, unnotched inner-webs of R2. •	Timing – Allen’s are known to migrate earlier in spring than Rufous, often Jan-March, before Rufous are expected in Inyo with the earliest Rufous spring migrants arriving the first week of March.

Bird believed to be continuing Allen's seen by Williams, as well others. P2, in my opinion doesn't show much of a notch, if any at all, which falls in line with some of the photos I've seen of immature males in published literature. If there is a notch of p2 it's very slight. P5 appears to have a spike. Bird in question also has green upper back with rufous along rump and tail, noted when feeding. Also have multiple recordings of believed  Allen's and Rufous; maybe they can be distinguished by further review of graph. Merlin, which I don't frequently trust on questionable birds, did pick up Allen's multiple times throughout 2 hour visit.  At the site, were at least 3 rufous hummingbirds of different ages as well.  By no means a hummingbird expert and will change once reviewed by one of the hummingbird experts if it's determined to be incorrect.

Birds A and B, (Mr A and Mr B now) are around as always. Mr B gave a tail shake revealing his pointy tail feathers as well.  From Sheri L. Williamson: (Name dropping!) Looks like you hit the jackpot! I concur that you've got TWO juvenile male Allen's. Besides the widths and shapes of the rectrices (conveniently entirely adult in B), the advanced primary molt of both birds is also more consistent with juvenile Allen's than juvenile Rufous. Congratulations!  Sheri L. Williamson, Director/Naturalist Southeastern Arizona Bird Observatory Bisbee, Arizona

Bird B is my original Allen's. It has no iridescent side feathers and a fairly large patch on its central throat. Lancelate tail feathers, narrow R5 and green back, see diagnostic photo 15 Dec, S98935894. Today I managed another photo of bird B tail feathers and again note the very narrow R5 characteristic of an Allen's.  Bird A has iridescent gorget feathers on the sides of its throat and a small number of darker feathers on the central throat. Lancelate tail feathers, narrow R5 and green back, see diagnostic photo 20 Dec, S99191485.  Audio Stats		 22 audio recordings. BirdNET 100% er ID's: 	16	Allen's 	2	Rufous 	3	Anna's  Of the many recordings, five were captured simultaneously on my recorder and my Android using Merlin. Of the five, Merlin ID'd all as Allen's while BirdNET ID'd four as Allen's 100% and one as 100% Allens / 100% Rufous.  Cannot be 100% both!  WOOHOO.... From Sheri L. Williamson: Looks like you hit the jackpot! I concur that you've got TWO juvenile male Allen's. Besides the widths and shapes of the rectrices (conveniently entirely adult in B), the advanced primary molt of both birds is also more consistent with juvenile Allen's than juvenile Rufous.  Congratulations!  Sheri L. Williamson, Director/Naturalist Southeastern Arizona Bird Observatory Bisbee, Arizona

Continuing stakeout found by Tom Uslan, been frequenting his feeders between ~4 pm and dusk. Adult male with many spread tail shots taken. Fully green back, head, and rump. Unnotched R2 and pin like R4 and R5. Aggressively defending feeders from Anna’s and offering great looks. Unfortunately, the bird never displayed but the date and location suggests this bird could be breeding locally. A female selasphorus was also spotted which could potentially be his mate. What an amazing find by Tom and a fantastic job documenting the spread tail. Not an easy thing to do. Many thanks for his hospitality. For those interested, you can contact Tom via his email that is on his ebird profile.

Observation Details: Second year male with adult tail feathers, as per Kelly Bryan's measurements when he caught and banded the bird. R2 lanceolate (not broad and notched), outer tail feathers very narrow and pin-like. Otherwise, mostly rufous below and green backed/capped, with roughly only 15-20% of the throat with orange gorget feathers grown in- shown in the second photo.   A second Selasphorus sp. hummer has also been frequenting the yard, but was NOT caught or banded. This second Selasphorus also shows a green back and orange below, but has well over half of the throat with orange gorget feathers, and also is heard making typical Rufous Hummingbird-like calls (and has been present since early December). The Allen's has only been around for a few weeks.

After two full days of research and many hours watching orange hummingbirds, I believe this bird to be an Allen's. Due to moderate wear, the R2s on this bird leave a bit to be desired when it comes to a decisive notch/lack thereof. Media notes: NOTES: BRUSH COVERED SLOPE - MANY FLOWERS.         [This is the ONLY recording available for this one!  It contains mostly wing buzzing by a flying male, but there are also numerous Chip Notes and at least two relatively good Chatters (see Figure 3A of BNA account).  The recording begins with several sets of hard, doubled Chip Notes, apparently given by a male in flight (0:04-0:06), these followed by softer Chips that were likely given by a perched bird (0:07-0:24).  There are three Chatters, possibly given by multiple birds at 0:27-0:34, followed by more hard Chip Notes and then several more Chatters at 0:49-0:54.  Most of the rest of the recording has wing buzzing by a male in flight, but there are Chip notes scattered about and several more Chatters in the background.  Quality changed from 1-2 to 2, 2-1 (signal is generally quite weak, but there is a GOOD Chatter at 0:26-0:29) - CAM - 2 May 2005].

The sound heard at :20 is produced on the final dive at the bottom and in close proximity to the focal point.

As I have observed this hummingbird this morning it is becoming apparent that it is more likely an Allen's rather than a Rufous.  It has a dull green cap on a flat head and the green plumage extends most heavily down the middle of the back and fades out to just above the rump.  The green feathers also run along the side of the back just above the top of the wings.    The hummingbird is an adult male with a complete gorget.  The tips of the wings are in poor condition and it is missing all but about three tail feathers.  10-3-22  After reviewing photos and a couple of online sources I believe the tail feather on the left of the photo is the R2 and it is narrow like an Allen’s and not notched like a Rufous.  If this is the case then this is an Allen's Hummingbird.  Note:  I was corrected by Harlan Stewart on the tail feathers. He believes they are either 3, 4, or 5.

I am getting frustrated with the Rufous/Allen situation in the garden. Today I definitely note two DIFFERENT orange hummingbirds. Looking over today's photos as well as photos from all previous sightings, it is apparent that both birds are around. Additionally, I see evidence on each of them to claim an Allen's ID. I have photos of each with the outer retrices being very narrow. Bird B 15 Dec photo, Bird A 20 Dec photo. Recordings today have BirdNET ID's of both Allen's and Rufous (above).   So, either I have one Allen's and one Rufous, or two Allen's, but I most certainly have two birds! Bird A has iridescent gorget feathers on the sides of its throat and a small number of darker feathers on the central throat. Bird B is my original Allen's (so shoot me). It has no iridescent side feathers and a fairly large patch on its central throat. Note Bird B molt P1-8, P9-10 still to go.

Lancelate tail feathers and green back, and Allen's audio call (BirdNET 100%). This individual is well along in its primaries molt, only P9 and P10 to go. P1-P8 all growing in. By contrast, the Rufous last seen on 5 Dec still has old primaries P5-P10 and last winter Mr Feroce only got to P9-P10 in late January. So, another possible distinguishing feature between SE Tx Rufous and Allen's. Note 22 December. A second Allen's in the garden. I have designated this 15 Dec bird as bird "B". Bird B is my original Allen's (so shoot me). It has no iridescent side feathers and a fairly large patch on its central throat.

Observation Details: *Very rare; ~4th for Cape May County. Rufous-type hummer, first discovered by Evelyn Lovitz in her garden earlier this morning. Worn imm male; age/sex determined by female-type plumage aspect with extensive rufous rump and base of tail (bases to r1), directly abutting black tail tip. Also, heavily stippled throat all the way to chin made up of neatly arranged spots with even pale fringing, all indicate imm male. Several features indicate Allen's, most importantly, very narrow rectrices (whole folded tail looks narrow) with lanceolate r2 showing no notch, and very slim r5. Also, this bird is quite worn, more so than a Rufous would normally be at this date, but appropriate for the earlier breeding phenology of Allen's. There are a good number of fresh feathers coming in around the head and body, including rufous feathers on the cheeks and flanks, and green feathers on the back and nape (appropriate for adult male Allen's). A particularly large splotch of reflective orange gorget feathers may also include some new feathers. No evidence of primary molt. Defending garden from nearby Ruby-throats; "zeee-chupity-chup" chase call sounds very much like Rufous.

His comments: "Included in the group is the director of the Bird Banding Laboratory in Laurel, Maryland (DC), Bruce Peterjohn.  Although I knew your bird's ID the minute I saw it on my iPhone, I just showed your excellent tail spread pictures to Bruce and independently he verified my ID.  With complete confidence your bird is a hatching year (HY) male Allen's Hummingbird. Observation Details: First observation on 10/24. Spread tail photos show narrow R5 and no notch on R2. Plumage on body feathers reveal recent molt of fresh green. Audio Spectrogram analysis distinguish the visible variation of initial contact call between ALHU and RUHU. ALHU contact/warning call can be seen on the spectrogram at the 3, 12, and 19-second mark. RUHU contact/warning calls can be heard at 5.5 and 12.5-second mark.

Observation Details: Flagged as rare; continuing for some time at feeders of Debbie Beer. For anyone chasing, please review rules first; in short park on street, stay off grass/yard itself, wear a mask at all times, be respectful of neighbors and neighborhood. Chunky, small and prominently orange-toned hummingbird. Largely separable from other Selasphorus hummingbirds by structure, smaller and shorter-tailed than BTHU with overall more and brighter orange-buff tones. Larger than CAHU and not nearly so short-tailed or short-billed. Essentially identical to RUHU and not separable from view we got, but separated previously and identified confidently through banding. Observation Details: Bird believed to be continuing Allen's seen by Williams, as well others. P2, in my opinion doesn't show much of a notch, if any at all, which falls in line with some of the photos I've seen of immature males in published literature. If there is a notch of p2 it's very slight. P5 appears to have a spike. Bird in question also has green upper back with rufous along rump and tail, noted when feeding. Also have multiple recordings of believed  Allen's and Rufous; maybe they can be distinguished by further review of graph. Merlin, which I don't frequently trust on questionable birds, did pick up Allen's multiple times throughout 2 hour visit.  At the site, were at least 3 rufous hummingbirds of different ages as well.  By no means a hummingbird expert and will change once reviewed by one of the hummingbird experts if it's determined to be incorrect.

We think this is a subadult male adult Allen's pending comments.  Green back on a male selas. is often the hallmark of Allen's.  This bird is green-backed, but we are told that subadult male Rufous can also have green back in the fall, with more rufous on the top of the head, neck and edges of the back than an Allen's.  Still thinking about where this bird falls on those other details.  Looking at the tail feathers, it seems to lack the notching that would be expected in a Rufous, and the outer tail seems pinnate, arguing for Allen's. It seems to me that Tena Gardiner's tail photo taken simultaneously next to us nails it as an Allen's, so based on that, I am moving it to Allen's.  However, further expert comments may make a final determination.   Please drop your opinion and thoughts in the Harris County rare bird alert.

This bird is green-backed, but subadult male Rufous can also have green back in the fall, with more rufous on the top of the head, neck and edges of the back than an Allen's. The crown on this bird is dark grayish, arguing for Allen's.  Looking at the tail feathers in my photo 573A5366-3 below, there may be extremely slight notching but this extremely slight notching is still in line with Allen's reference photos on Sheri Williamson's  flickr site, reference noted below.  Tena Gardiner's better tail photo taken simultaneously next to us seems to nail it as an Allen's, as compared with the references on Sheri Williamson's flickr Allen's gallery, which is the strongest evidence.  The outer tail feather in my profile flight photo below also seems pinnate, arguing for Allen's.  We are told that the timing of the gorget moult is also consistent with Allen's.     Reference Footnote:  See Sheri-Williamson's Flickr Allen's Gallery and note the Huntington Beach California Allen's photo by Eric Lu (x73-3584-1 unambiguous Allen's)..R2 has a slight indentation and all the tail feathers seem identical in shape to everyone's photos of this Houston bird.

Observation Details: Both fledglings seen at once. Female feeding them periodically. A CASJ was perched in a bush very close to the refurbished but not yet occupied nest and the female was very agitated. When the jay flew away the fledglings then became visible as well as other birds. At one point one of the fledglings got too close to the other and they physically got into a tussle and flew vertically several times. I guess their territorial behavior starts as soon as they leave the nest! A male periodically would perform the courtship display.

Media notes: age revised to "adult female," per Sheri Williamson, as to this photo
Observation Details: chase flights and Selasphorus-characteristic chase calls around Grevillea lanigera and bottlebrush in the front yard, often interacting with male Anna's there as well. I think these two have been here a week, and today I got some photos showing tail pattern of one bright juv. It is a juv female: note the juv-patterned throat, the lack of indentation on R2, the broad band of green separating rufous base from the black tip on R1, and the relatively narrow R5; also extensively rufous rump. Not all those characters are diagnostic but together should be. Based on the literature and our experience in the yard, I think that during the first 2 weeks of July, the juvs are (almost) always Allen's while the adults are (almost) always Rufous but after mid-July the appearance of juv Rufous and fewer adults complicate matters, and then in August the juv Rufous will be heavily dominate with Allen's essentially disappearing by mid-August. UPDATE: Sheri Williamson has put this back in our queue as an adult female Allen's. This is the first time I've had anyone ask an observer to amend a age/sex designation, but I'm happy to change the photo to "adult female Allen's."

Locality: Rebecca's Home - 205 Blackburn Ave. Menlo Park, CA
Observation Details: Studied the bird at close range for several minutes and took numerous photos. Adult female selasphorus hummingbirds have an orange-red spot in the middle of their throat. This bird did not have a spot.  According to Sibley’s Bird Guide, juvenile Allen’s hummingbirds can be present as early as the month of February. Juvenile Rufous Hummingbirds not until the month of June.  Due to the lack of an orange-red spot in the middle of the throat and the timing,  plus geography, for the presence of juveniles, I believe the photos are of a juvenile Allen’s Hummingbird.

Go home little colibri!

Observation Details: Private residence.  Access allowed.  Rules below.  The bird was banded by Bruce Peterjohn on 16 Nov 2021 and determined to be a hatch year female Allen's Hummingbird.  Access Rules:  Visiting Hours:  The bird comes to the feeder all day long, however, does not seem to be on any regular schedule.  Visiting hours are restricted to 9:00 am to 3:00 pm.    Where to park:  Limited street parking.  Do not block neighbors’ driveways.   Please be respectful of parking on neighbors' lawns (do unto others.....).  Please carpool as much as possible.   For those who don’t mind walking, you can help alleviate parking issues by parking in Liberty Plaza where Outback Steakhouse is.  It is a half mile walk from there.    Address:  257 Delaplane Ave., Newark, DE 19711 Hosts:  Diane and Steve Freebery   It is not necessary to contact us prior to coming.   No restroom facilities available.      How to view the bird:  Walk to the bottom of the driveway at the south side of the house.  Look up at the feeder(s) hanging above the deck railing.  Please stay on the driveway behind the rope barrier.  PLEASE LIMIT the group size watching for the bird to 5 people at a time.   This may mean you need to wait up at the top of the driveway until someone ahead of you leaves.   Please add these rules to the description of the bird in all eBird reports.   Thank you, Steve and Diane Freebery

Observation Details: Walking on my block, I caught sight of a hummingbird as it flew past me from behind and shot up toward the top of an evergreen, where it zipped about for about 10 seconds in the company of a ruby-crowned kinglet, which proceeded to chase it off. The hummingbird was distinctly orange/rufous-colored in places. It returned and hung around for a while. Photos.  Update January 13, 2021: Confirmed as female Allen's Hummingbird. Hummingbird bander Sandy Lockerman was able to examine her in hand, take measurements, and confirm that her leg band was a match with the female Allen's – nicknamed Allena – that she banded in Delaware County, PA, on the Beer/Binns property in December 2020. Remarkable.

The ID of Allen's Hummingbird was determined by precise measurements of the wing, tail, culmen (bill) and especially of the narrow outer tail feather (R5). Though R2, the secondmost inner tail feather was not especially narrow, it lacked an obvious "notch" and is within the variation for Allen's. As many of you know, a notched R2 is a trait suggestive of Rufous Hummingbird which is the species very similar to Allen's and much more common in Wisconsin. The ID of this bird was made with the guidance of my mentor and veteran hummingbird bander, Kelly Bryan of West Texas Avian Research

I have reported on the garden birds daily since 15 Dec. The second Allen's, Mr A, showed up on 18 Dec and photos with diagnostic tail feather spread were obtained on the 20th. Yet as of 3 Jan eBird steadfastly maintains that two Allen's are not allowed and my signtings remain locked in the "unconfirmed" eBird vault.  Once again, I remind you that Sheri Williamson has reviewed and confirmed BOTH birds as bona-fide Allen's based on tail spread and primary molt progress from photos.  [Sheri L. Williamson, Director/Naturalist, Southeastern Arizona Bird Observatory, Author of the Peterson Field guide to north American Hummingbirds.]  Mr A has iridescent gorget feathers on the sides of its throat and a small number of darker feathers on the central throat. Lancelate tail feathers, narrow R5 and green back, see diagnostic photo 20 Dec, S99191485. Mr B is my original Allen's. It has no iridescent side feathers and a fairly large patch on its central throat. Lancelate tail feathers, narrow R5 and green back, see diagnostic photo 15 Dec, S98935894.  Mr A today. I noted his feeder visit schedule as follows: 9:12, 9:32, 9:39, 9:53, 10:01, 10:11, 10:23, 10:34. Eight visits over 82 minutes, 10 minute interval average. Its cold out there! Outside temperatures in low 30's.  Mr B today. Me B showed up at 10:57 just shortly before I called it a day (on account of I was freezing!).   Finally, two audio clips identified as Allen's on BirdNET.

Very Access Rules: Visiting Hours: The bird comes to the feeder all day long, however, does not seem to be on any regular schedule. Visiting hours are restricted to 9:00 am to 3:00 pm.  Where to park: Limited street parking. Do not block neighbors’ driveways. Please be respectful of parking on neighbors' lawns (do unto others.....). Please carpool as much as possible. Address: 257 Delaplane Ave., Newark, DE 19711 Hosts: Diane and Steve Freebery  It is not necessary to contact us prior to coming.  No restroom facilities available.  How to view the bird: Walk to the bottom of the driveway at the south side of the house. Look up at the feeder(s) hanging above the deck railing. Please stay on the driveway behind the rope barrier.  PLEASE LIMIT the group size watching for the bird to 5 people at a time. This may mean you need to wait up at the top of the driveway until someone ahead of you leaves.  Please add these rules to the description of the bird in all eBird reports.  Thank you, Steve and Diane Freebery"

Bird B is my original Allen's. It has no iridescent side feathers and a fairly large patch on its central throat. Lancelate tail feathers, narrow R5 and green back, see diagnostic photo 15 Dec, S98935894. Today I managed another photo of bird B tail feathers and again note the very narrow R5 characteristic of an Allen's.  Bird A has iridescent gorget feathers on the sides of its throat and a small number of darker feathers on the central throat. Lancelate tail feathers, narrow R5 and green back, see diagnostic photo 20 Dec, S99191485.  Audio Stats		 22 audio recordings. BirdNET 100% er ID's: 	16	Allen's 	2	Rufous 	3	Anna's  Of the many recordings, five were captured simultaneously on my recorder and my Android using Merlin. Of the five, Merlin ID'd all as Allen's while BirdNET ID'd four as Allen's 100% and one as 100% Allens / 100% Rufous.  Cannot be 100% both!  WOOHOO.... From Sheri L. Williamson: Looks like you hit the jackpot! I concur that you've got TWO juvenile male Allen's. Besides the widths and shapes of the rectrices (conveniently entirely adult in B), the advanced primary molt of both birds is also more consistent with juvenile Allen's than juvenile Rufous.  Congratulations!  Sheri L. Williamson, Director/Naturalist Southeastern Arizona Bird Observatory Bisbee, Arizona

I am getting frustrated with the Rufous/Allen situation in the garden. Today I definitely note two DIFFERENT orange hummingbirds. Looking over today's photos as well as photos from all previous sightings, it is apparent that both birds are around. Additionally, I see evidence on each of them to claim an Allen's ID. I have photos of each with the outer retrices being very narrow. Bird B 15 Dec photo, Bird A 20 Dec photo. Recordings today have BirdNET ID's of both Allen's and Rufous (above).   So, either I have one Allen's and one Rufous, or two Allen's, but I most certainly have two birds! Bird A has iridescent gorget feathers on the sides of its throat and a small number of darker feathers on the central throat. Bird B is my original Allen's (so shoot me). It has no iridescent side feathers and a fairly large patch on its central throat. Note Bird B molt P1-8, P9-10 still to go.

Continuing stakeout found by Tom Uslan, been frequenting his feeders between ~4 pm and dusk. Adult male with many spread tail shots taken. Fully green back, head, and rump. Unnotched R2 and pin like R4 and R5. Aggressively defending feeders from Anna’s and offering great looks. Unfortunately, the bird never displayed but the date and location suggests this bird could be breeding locally. A female selasphorus was also spotted which could potentially be his mate. What an amazing find by Tom and a fantastic job documenting the spread tail. Not an easy thing to do. Many thanks for his hospitality. For those interested, you can contact Tom via his email that is on his ebird profile.

*Very rare; ~4th for Cape May County. Rufous-type hummer, first discovered by Evelyn Lovitz in her garden earlier this morning. Worn imm male; age/sex determined by female-type plumage aspect with extensive rufous rump and base of tail (bases to r1), directly abutting black tail tip. Also, heavily stippled throat all the way to chin made up of neatly arranged spots with even pale fringing, all indicate imm male. Several features indicate Allen's, most importantly, very narrow rectrices (whole folded tail looks narrow) with lanceolate r2 showing no notch, and very slim r5. Also, this bird is quite worn, more so than a Rufous would normally be at this date, but appropriate for the earlier breeding phenology of Allen's. There are a good number of fresh feathers coming in around the head and body, including rufous feathers on the cheeks and flanks, and green feathers on the back and nape (appropriate for adult male Allen's). A particularly large splotch of reflective orange gorget feathers may also include some new feathers. No evidence of primary molt. Defending garden from nearby Ruby-throats; "zeee-chupity-chup" chase call sounds very much like Rufous.

Green backed RUHU are not uncommon when seen in the state so tail was used to ID bird. Tail feathers were thinner and more narrow with lanceolates. Where to park: Limited street parking. Do not block neighbors’ driveways. Please be respectful of parking on neighbors' lawns (do unto others.....). Please carpool as much as possible. For those who don’t mind walking, you can help alleviate parking issues by parking in Liberty Plaza where Outback Steakhouse is. It is a half mile walk from there.   Address: 257 Delaplane Ave., Newark, DE 19711 Hosts: Diane and Steve Freebery  It is not necessary to contact us prior to coming.  No restroom facilities available.   How to view the bird: Walk to the bottom of the driveway at the south side of the house. Look up at the feeder(s) hanging above the deck railing. Please stay on the driveway behind the rope barrier.  PLEASE LIMIT the group size watching for the bird to 5 people at a time. This may mean you need to wait up at the top of the driveway until someone ahead of you leaves.   Please add these rules to the description of the bird in all eBird reports.  Thank you, Steve and Diane Freebery

September 3 update: R/A hummer identified by Kelly Bryan as a juvenile male ALHU. Thank you, Kelly.   Narrow R4 and R5.  R2 does not appear to be notched, so better for ALHU.  I would guess that this is an immature male. Green back and crown.  Bird probably came to the yard this morning.  First seen around 0830 and was present throughout the day.  Very aggressive.  At first perched in nearby tree, but, eventually, pretty much parked on the far side of the feeder.  Didn't go to flowers.  Spread its tail whenever it was chasing and/or challenging another hummer.  Started raining after 10 a.m., so only dry bird images.  Wet bird shown in my next report.  Weather was overcast and in the mid 70s all day.  Very light rain on and off  all day and expected to continue into the next day.

Continuing. First state record of Allen's Hummingbird. See attached photos. Brainard Palmer-Ball and Mark Monroe banded this bird yesterday, Oct. 7, 2023. Here are their notes... "Captured for ID and banding; released after measurements taken and banding; returned to feeder within an hour or so. HY male with circa 10 reflective gorget feathers including a few large ones along the margin of the throat/gorget, green back, rufous rump, strong rufous wash on flanks, and rects largely rufous in color. Little emargination on tip of r2, very narrow r5 (1.98 mm), first generation r1 on left side already replaced. Wing: 39.38 mm; exposed culmen: 17.83 mm; tail 24 mm; striations present in the form of one long groove over one-half length of bill. Photos and measurements shared with several other hummingbird banders with much more experience with Rufous/Allen's. All agreed with ID of Allen's."

A CASJ was perched in a bush very close to the refurbished but not yet occupied nest and the female was very agitated. At one point one of the fledglings got too close to the other and they physically got into a tussle and flew vertically several times. I guess their territorial behavior starts as soon as they leave the nest! A male periodically would perform the courtship display.

Observation Details: Studied the bird at close range for several minutes and took numerous photos. Adult female selasphorus hummingbirds have an orange-red spot in the middle of their throat. This bird did not have a spot.  According to Sibley’s Bird Guide, juvenile Allen’s hummingbirds can be present as early as the month of February. Juvenile Rufous Hummingbirds not until the month of June.  Due to the lack of an orange-red spot in the middle of the throat and the timing,  plus geography, for the presence of juveniles, I believe the photos are of a juvenile Allen’s Hummingbird.

I was happy to see this Allen's Hummingbird in the blackberries vines just west of the intersection of Oak Alley and China Cove Trails. I found Allen's Hummingbirds there in April of 2018, 2019, and 2020, but I didn't find one there last year. This one, as did the ones in the previous years, returned again and again to the same perch in the blackberries so it was easy to get good looks.

As visible in the first photo, this female was in the midst of adding more material to her nest when I found her. (First observed in-flight carrying nest material, in fact--hence how I found the nest).  Nest is visible from the trail, allowing for me to photograph without disturbing the bird or her environment. Spent only a quick moment there to give her space.  As a reminder, nesting season means we must all be extra careful not to disturb our feathered friends, which goes especially for something like photographing a hummer nest. In this particular scenario, I made the judgment call that I could safety take these photos given that: 1. the location of the nest meant it could be photographed without me leaving the marked trail or interfering with the area physically in any way; 2. the bird, who I had first observed in flight several feet away, was comfortable enough with my presence to land on the nest while I was observing her with my bins (hence how I discovered it in the first place), and proceeded with her task of adding material to the nest with little regard for me; 3. I did not need more than fifteen seconds or so to take some shots before leaving her be. So if you do happen to find this bird, or any other nesting in the area, please be mindful of their safety and well-being and be sure (whether photographing or simply observing) never to disturb the area in any way that could endanger the nest or render it more visible to predators, to aways check that the birds/nestlings are not stressed or liable to abandon the nest, and to avoid spending too much time there lest you attract the attention of nearby predators.

Continuing stakeout found by Tom Uslan, been frequenting his feeders between ~4 pm and dusk. Adult male with many spread tail shots taken. Fully green back, head, and rump. Unnotched R2 and pin like R4 and R5. Aggressively defending feeders from Anna’s and offering great looks. Unfortunately, the bird never displayed but the date and location suggests this bird could be breeding locally. A female selasphorus was also spotted which could potentially be his mate. What an amazing find by Tom and a fantastic job documenting the spread tail. Not an easy thing to do. Many thanks for his hospitality. Continuing. First state record of Allen's Hummingbird. See attached photos. Brainard Palmer-Ball and Mark Monroe banded this bird yesterday, Oct. 7, 2023. Here are their notes... "Captured for ID and banding; released after measurements taken and banding; returned to feeder within an hour or so. HY male with circa 10 reflective gorget feathers including a few large ones along the margin of the throat/gorget, green back, rufous rump, strong rufous wash on flanks, and rects largely rufous in color. Little emargination on tip of r2, very narrow r5 (1.98 mm), first generation r1 on left side already replaced. Wing: 39.38 mm; exposed culmen: 17.83 mm; tail 24 mm; striations present in the form of one long groove over one-half length of bill. Photos and measurements shared with several other hummingbird banders with much more experience with Rufous/Allen's. All agreed with ID of Allen's."

Locality: Gary Nunn wildlife garden Pacific Beach

Observation Details: Bird believed to be continuing Allen's seen by Williams, as well others. P2, in my opinion doesn't show much of a notch, if any at all, which falls in line with some of the photos I've seen of immature males in published literature. If there is a notch of p2 it's very slight. P5 appears to have a spike. Bird in question also has green upper back with rufous along rump and tail, noted when feeding. Also have multiple recordings of believed  Allen's and Rufous; maybe they can be distinguished by further review of graph. Merlin, which I don't frequently trust on questionable birds, did pick up Allen's multiple times throughout 2 hour visit.  At the site, were at least 3 rufous hummingbirds of different ages as well.  By no means a hummingbird expert and will change once reviewed by one of the hummingbird experts if it's determined to be incorrect.

Media notes: This photo initially gave me pause that there might be a little bit of notch in the R2, but it is comparable still to Sheri Williamson's flickr reference photos of Allen's (such as the Huntington Beach photo by Eric Lu).
Observation Details: Subadult male adult Allen's pending expert review.  Green back on a male selasphorus is often the hallmark of Allen's.  This bird is green-backed, but subadult male Rufous can also have green back in the fall, with more rufous on the top of the head, neck and edges of the back than an Allen's. The crown on this bird is dark grayish, arguing for Allen's.  Looking at the tail feathers in my photo 573A5366-3 below, there may be extremely slight notching but this extremely slight notching is still in line with Allen's reference photos on Sheri Williamson's  flickr site, reference noted below.  Tena Gardiner's better tail photo taken simultaneously next to us seems to nail it as an Allen's, as compared with the references on Sheri Williamson's flickr Allen's gallery, which is the strongest evidence.  The outer tail feather in my profile flight photo below also seems pinnate, arguing for Allen's.  We are told that the timing of the gorget moult is also consistent with Allen's.     Reference Footnote:  See Sheri-Williamson's Flickr Allen's Gallery and note the Huntington Beach California Allen's photo by Eric Lu (x73-3584-1 unambiguous Allen's)..R2 has a slight indentation and all the tail feathers seem identical in shape to everyone's photos of this Houston bird.

We think this is a subadult male adult Allen's pending comments.  Green back on a male selas. is often the hallmark of Allen's.  This bird is green-backed, but we are told that subadult male Rufous can also have green back in the fall, with more rufous on the top of the head, neck and edges of the back than an Allen's.  Still thinking about where this bird falls on those other details.  Looking at the tail feathers, it seems to lack the notching that would be expected in a Rufous, and the outer tail seems pinnate, arguing for Allen's. It seems to me that Tena Gardiner's tail photo taken simultaneously next to us nails it as an Allen's, so based on that, I am moving it to Allen's.  However, further expert comments may make a final determination.   Please drop your opinion and thoughts in the Harris County rare bird alert.

Observation Details: This bird was assumed to be a Rufous Hummingbird. Ric Payne got several doc shots of this hummingbird in November, including a spread tail photo. After researching, studying diagrams and consulting experts, the consensus was that R5 and R4 looked appropriately thin enough for Allen’s; however, photos can be deceiving and more were needed. We went hoping to get diagnostic photos but failed with good spread tail shots. At this point we knew it could never be called unless the bird was in hand, measured and banded. On 12/5 Allen Chartier was able to capture and band the bird and confirmed it as an Allen’s Hummingbird. This is only the second Ohio record. A big thank you to both homeowners who graciously let us view their feeders and especially to Molly who worked with Allen Chartier to have the bird banded.

The ID of Allen's Hummingbird was determined by precise measurements of the wing, tail, culmen (bill) and especially of the narrow outer tail feather (R5). Though R2, the secondmost inner tail feather was not especially narrow, it lacked an obvious "notch" and is within the variation for Allen's. As many of you know, a notched R2 is a trait suggestive of Rufous Hummingbird which is the species very similar to Allen's and much more common in Wisconsin. The ID of this bird was made with the guidance of my mentor and veteran hummingbird bander, Kelly Bryan of West Texas Avian Research
